<subSubSection pageId="138" pageNumber="139" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="138.[189,324,835,861]" box="[189,324,835,861]" pageId="138" pageNumber="139">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,835,861]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="138" pageNumber="139" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,835,861]" pageId="138" pageNumber="139">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="138.[189,1398,882,982]" pageId="138" pageNumber="139">
Although the etymology of the species name was unspecified, ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1936" box="[934,1050,882,908]" class="Arachnida" family="Charinidae" genus="Charinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amblypygi" pageId="138" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diblemma">
<emphasis box="[934,1050,882,908]" italics="true" pageId="138" pageNumber="139">diblemma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ refers to the presence of two eyes, from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[447,470,919,945]" italics="true" pageId="138" pageNumber="139">di</emphasis>
-‘ (‘two’) and the Greek ‘ 
<emphasis box="[775,868,919,945]" italics="true" pageId="138" pageNumber="139">blemma</emphasis>
’ (‘glance’), as Simon (1936) considered this species to possess only the median pair.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
